```

To solve this, we need to show that for any `x ∈ α × β`, `x` is in the support of the distribution `(fun x1 x2 => (x1, x2)) ∘ (fun a b ↦ (a, b))` where `fun a b ↦ (a, b)` is the product of the two sample distributions.

This means that `x ∈ support D` where `D` is the distribution `(fun x1 x2 => (x1, x2)) ∘ (fun a b ↦ (a, b))`.

The definition of support is the set of elements `y` such that `Pr[= y | D] > 0`.

In our case, for any `x = (a, b) ∈ α × β`, `Pr[(a, b) ∈ α × β] = Pr[= a | selectElem α] * Pr[= b | selectElem β]`.

Since `x` is an arbitrary element of `α × β`, we need to show that for all `a ∈ α, b ∈ β`, `Pr[= a | selectElem α] * Pr[= b | selectElem β] > 0`.

From `hα` (which is `inst✝¹`), we have `mem_support_selectElem : ∀ (y : α), y ∈ support selectElem α`.
Similarly, for `β`, we have `mem_support_selectElem β : ∀ (y : β), y ∈ support selectElem β`.

So for any `a ∈ α`, `a ∈ support selectElem α`, which means `Pr[= a | selectElem α] > 0`.
Similarly, for any `b ∈ β`, `b ∈ support selectElem β`, which means `Pr[= b | selectElem β] > 0`.

Therefore, for any `a ∈ α, b ∈ β`, `Pr[= a | selectElem α] * Pr[= b | selectElem β] > 0`.

